<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-224-086  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 224 086.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>CommunicationsWeek  May 1 1989 n246 p6(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Fraud: costly to private nets. (includes related article APhreaker's Ways)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Vinton, Bob.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The inadequacy of telephone system security is costing USbusinesses as much as $500 million annually.andP;  Systems using PBXsare most vulnerable to unauthorized use by hackers and phonephreakers, who may use lost or stolen phone credit cards, an 800line, or gain access to the PBX through its maintenance port.andP;  APBX cannot tell where a call is originating.andP;  Often privatenetworks that are victimized do not realize it until after thefact, and are reluctant to publicize their losses.andP;  Long distanceand local carriers also avoid such negative publicity, and do nottake any responsibility for network security.andP;  Companies shouldinstall such safeguards as automatic callback modems, rapididentification equipment, and complex access codes before hackersand phreakers strike.andP;  Some victims have been held liable for$250,000 worth of unauthorized calls.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     FraudTelecommunicationsComputer HackersCost of CommunicationsComputer CrimesSecurityNetworks.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>